fonline access with authorization2star  aThe Transformation of Plantation Politics explores the effects of black political exclusion, the sharecropping system, and white resistance on the Mississippi Delta's current economic and political situation. Sharon D. Wright Austin's extensive interviews with residents of the region shed light on the transformations and legacies of the Delta's political and economic institutions. While African Americans now hold most of the major political offices in the region and are no longer formally excluded from political participation, educational opportunities, or lucrative jobs, Wright Austin shows that white wealth and black poverty continue to be the norm partly because of the deeply entrenched legacies of the Delta's history. Contributing to a greater theoretical understanding of black political efforts, this book demonstrates a need for a strong level of black social capital, intergroup capital, financial capital, political capital, and a human capital of educated and skilled workers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican AmericanszMississippizDelta (Region)xPolitics and government. 0aAfrican AmericanszMississippizDelta (Region)xSocial conditions. 0aElite (Social sciences)zMississippizDelta (Region). 0aPlantation lifezMississippizDelta (Region). 0aPovertyxPolitical aspectszMississippizDelta (Region). 0aSocial capital (Sociology)zMississippizDelta (Region). 0aWhite peoplezMississippizDelta (Region)xSocial conditions. 0aWhiteszMississippizDelta (Region)xSocial conditions. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 aMorrison, Minion K. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY P